ole to play in the improvement and pe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rformance of all schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> regard of their designation, and as such </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as a pro-active interest in the governance and scrutiny of academies and free schools. </span></p><h1 style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">uthorities retain over 200 statutory responsibilities for children regardless of the settings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">they attend</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> for their education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Through the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">F</span><span style="color:#222222; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">ramework for the inspection of local authority arrangements for supporting school improvement, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> Ofsted has laid out clear </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">and robust expectations of how local a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">uthorities need to fulfil their responsibilities for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ensuring each child receives a high quality education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">.  There should be no tension between a diverse, self-improving school system and the involvement of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ocal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">uthority securing the best possible outc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">omes for all children in every setting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">Despite</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> local authorities having</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> no formal power of intervention in academies and free schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> they do have a moral and statutory duty to ensure those schools provide a high quality of education. As such l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">ocal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">authorities have a clear role in helping every school in their local area improve, yet there must be an acknowledgement that local solutions towards school improvement exist, and how each local authority fulfils their statutory duty in this area will be di</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">fferent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">. </span></h1><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The announcement of the establishment of eight regional commissioners for education by the Department for Education in December 2013 h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> added a new dimension to the intervention and monitoring of academies and free schools. At the moment it is u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nclear what role the new commissioners will have in monitoring and intervening in low performing academies that are not currently failing.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It must be the goal of all involved to prevent schools from failing in the first place, rather than simply issuing wa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rning notices or using other intervention powers after the failure has occurred. R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">egional commissioners will not be directly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> nor democratically</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> accountable locally and the size and structure of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> eight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> regions mean it is unlikely that they will be able t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o develop the detailed understanding of local schools that the local authority has. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Further clarification on the role of regional commissioners in monitoring and challenging low performing academies and free schools</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and their proposed interaction with the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> role of the local authority,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would be most welcome. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Chains of academies are not currently subject to inspection as local authorities are. We would advocate that inspection of academy chains, and the support they provide for their schools is subject to in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">spection by Ofsted in the future. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The underperformance of any school should be subject to local scrutiny, and if possible a locally provided solution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> should be found</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> before academy status is considered. At present any formal action</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> taken</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by a local authority to secure improved performance in an underperforming school, such as the use of warning notices or an IEB appears to be a trigger for the consideration of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">forced conversion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to academy status</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by the Department for Education</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Allowing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local authorities to intervene and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">secure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> locally delivered solutions to improve schools would be preferable to the swift conversion to academy status. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>